{
  "texts": [
    "This algorithm identifies an optimal hyperplane that segregates input data points by their class (e.g.",
    "relevant or irrelevant as in the case of automating the screening stage or classifying the input as having a high-risk or lowrisk bias) within an N-dimensional space (Cortes and Vapnik 1995) by employing a range of mathematical functions known as kernels.",
    "These kernels include linear, sigmoid, Gaussian, polynomial, nonlinear, and radial basis functions (Mahendra and Azizah 2023).",
    "The linear SVM is predominantly used in LR automation (Joachims 2006).",
    "Additional variations of SVM, such as the soft-margin polynomial and Evolutionary SVM (EvoSVM), have been proposed in other studies to enhance performance (Timsina et al. 2015)."
  ]
}